1
00:01:20,247 --> 00:01:23,983
I have of late, but wherefore I know not,

2
00:01:35,162 --> 00:01:38,063
lost all my mirth.

3
00:01:46,607 --> 00:01:49,174
What a piece of work is a man?

4
00:01:49,176 --> 00:01:50,676
How noble in reason?

5
00:01:50,678 --> 00:01:54,646
How infinite in faculties
and form and moving?

6
00:01:54,648 --> 00:01:57,750
How express and admirable in action?

7
00:01:57,752 --> 00:02:00,719
How like an angel in
apprehension? How like a god?

8
00:02:11,499 --> 00:02:13,766
<i>The beauty of the world,</i>

9
00:02:17,605 --> 00:02:19,671
<i>the paragon of animals,</i>

10
00:02:23,110 --> 00:02:25,277
<i>and yet, to me...</i>

11
00:02:28,082 --> 00:02:31,183
<i>What is this quintessence of dust?</i>

12
00:02:46,133 --> 00:02:49,168
<i>Though yet of Hamlet
our dear brother's death</i>

13
00:02:49,170 --> 00:02:51,370
<i>our memory be green,</i>

14
00:02:51,372 --> 00:02:54,840
<i>and that it us befitted
to bear our heart in grief</i>

15
00:02:54,842 --> 00:02:57,276
<i>and our whole kingdom to be contracted</i>

16
00:02:57,278 --> 00:02:59,678
<i>in one brow of woe.</i>

17
00:02:59,680 --> 00:03:02,681
Yet so far hath discretion
fought with nature

18
00:03:02,683 --> 00:03:05,417
that we with wisest sorrow think on him,

19
00:03:05,419 --> 00:03:08,387
<i>together with remembrance of ourselves.</i>

20
00:03:08,389 --> 00:03:12,558
Therefore our sometime sister,

21
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:14,526
now our queen,

22
00:03:14,528 --> 00:03:17,563
the imperial jointress
to this warlike state,

23
00:03:17,565 --> 00:03:21,300
<i>have we, as 'twere with a defeated joy...</i>

24
00:03:21,302 --> 00:03:25,237
<i>With an auspicious and dropping eye,</i>

25
00:03:25,239 --> 00:03:26,839
<i>with mirth in funeral</i>

26
00:03:26,841 --> 00:03:29,341
<i>and with dirge in marriage,</i>

27
00:03:29,343 --> 00:03:33,579
<i>in equal scale weighing
delight and dole...</i>

28
00:03:33,581 --> 00:03:38,484
taken to wife.

29
00:03:48,629 --> 00:03:52,164
Nor have we herein barred
your better wisdoms,

30
00:03:52,166 --> 00:03:54,867
which have freely gone
with this affair along.

31
00:03:54,869 --> 00:03:58,704
- For all...
- Our thanks.

32
00:04:02,176 --> 00:04:04,510
Now follows, that you know

33
00:04:04,512 --> 00:04:06,278
young Fortinbras,

34
00:04:06,280 --> 00:04:09,848
holding a weak supposal of our worth.

35
00:04:09,850 --> 00:04:11,850
<i>Or thinking by our late
dear brother's death</i>

36
00:04:11,852 --> 00:04:14,887
<i>our state to be disjoint
and out of frame,</i>

37
00:04:14,889 --> 00:04:18,457
<i>colleagued with the dream
of his advantage,</i>

38
00:04:18,459 --> 00:04:21,894
he hath not failed to pester
us with message,

39
00:04:21,896 --> 00:04:24,897
<i>importing the surrender of those lands</i>

40
00:04:24,899 --> 00:04:26,732
<i>lost by his father.</i>

41
00:04:26,734 --> 00:04:30,702
<i>With all bond of law,
to our most valiant brother.</i>

42
00:04:33,207 --> 00:04:34,940
So much for him.

43
00:04:47,821 --> 00:04:50,522
And now, Laertes, what's
the news with you?

44
00:04:50,524 --> 00:04:52,457
The head is not more native to the heart,

45
00:04:52,459 --> 00:04:54,226
the hand more instrumental to the mouth,

46
00:04:54,228 --> 00:04:56,328
than is the throne of
Denmark to thy father.

47
00:04:56,330 --> 00:04:58,463
What wouldst thou have, Laertes?

48
00:04:58,465 --> 00:05:01,500
My dread lord, your leave and
favor to return to France;

49
00:05:01,502 --> 00:05:04,937
From whence though willingly I come
to show my duty in your coronation,

50
00:05:04,939 --> 00:05:06,838
now, I must confess, that duty done,

51
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:09,241
my thoughts and wishes
bend again toward France.

52
00:05:09,243 --> 00:05:12,544
<i>- Have you your father's leave?
- What says Polonius?</i>

53
00:05:12,546 --> 00:05:16,848
He has, my lord, wrung
from me my slow leave

54
00:05:16,850 --> 00:05:19,985
by laboursome petition, and at last

55
00:05:19,987 --> 00:05:23,722
upon his will I sealed my hard consent.

56
00:05:23,724 --> 00:05:26,725
I do beseech you, give him leave to go.

57
00:05:26,727 --> 00:05:29,261
Take thy fair hour,
Laertes; Time be thine,

58
00:05:29,263 --> 00:05:33,232
and thy best grace spend it at thy will!

59
00:05:35,469 --> 00:05:37,436
<i>My cousin Hamlet,</i>

60
00:05:37,438 --> 00:05:39,972
<i>and my son...</i>

61
00:05:39,974 --> 00:05:42,975
<i>How is it that the clouds
still hang on you?</i>

62
00:05:42,977 --> 00:05:45,277
Hamlet...

63
00:05:45,279 --> 00:05:47,346
cast thy nighted color off,

64
00:05:47,348 --> 00:05:50,882
and let thine eye look
like a friend on Denmark.

65
00:05:50,884 --> 00:05:52,818
Do not forever with thy vailed lids

66
00:05:52,820 --> 00:05:55,954
seek for thy noble father in the dust.

67
00:05:55,956 --> 00:05:57,923
<i>Thou know'st 'tis common;</i>

68
00:05:57,925 --> 00:06:01,994
All that lives must die, passing
through nature to eternity.

69
00:06:01,996 --> 00:06:03,829
Ay, madam, it is common.

70
00:06:03,831 --> 00:06:08,767
If it be, why seems it
so particular with thee?

71
00:06:08,769 --> 00:06:11,370
Seems, Madam.

72
00:06:13,741 --> 00:06:17,709
Nay, it is.
I know not "seems."

73
00:06:17,711 --> 00:06:19,945
<i>'Tis not alone my inky cloak,
good Mother,</i>

74
00:06:19,947 --> 00:06:23,949
nor customary suits of solemn black,

75
00:06:23,951 --> 00:06:26,985
nor windy suspiration of forced breath.

76
00:06:26,987 --> 00:06:30,756
No, nor the fruitful river in the eye,

77
00:06:30,758 --> 00:06:32,724
that can denote me truly.

78
00:06:32,726 --> 00:06:35,460
These indeed seem,

79
00:06:35,462 --> 00:06:38,764
for they are actions
that a man might play.

80
00:06:38,766 --> 00:06:40,999
But I have that within
which passeth show,

81
00:06:41,001 --> 00:06:44,069
these but the trappings
and the suits of woe.

82
00:06:48,709 --> 00:06:51,076
'Tis sweet and commendable
in your nature, Hamlet,

83
00:06:51,078 --> 00:06:54,046
to give these mourning
duties to your father.

84
00:06:54,048 --> 00:06:56,848
But that father lost, lost his,

85
00:06:56,850 --> 00:07:00,052
and the survivor bound in
filial obligation for some term

86
00:07:00,054 --> 00:07:01,920
to do obsequious sorrow.

87
00:07:01,922 --> 00:07:04,389
But to persevere in obdurate condolement

88
00:07:04,391 --> 00:07:05,891
is a course of impious stubbornness;

89
00:07:05,893 --> 00:07:08,393
'Tis an unmanly grief.

90
00:07:09,530 --> 00:07:12,097
It shows a will most incorrect to heaven.

91
00:07:12,099 --> 00:07:14,666
A heart unfortified, a mind impatient.

92
00:07:14,668 --> 00:07:17,035
For your intent on going back
to school in Wittenberg,

93
00:07:17,037 --> 00:07:19,471
it is most retrograde to our desire,

94
00:07:19,473 --> 00:07:22,341
and we beseech you, bend you

95
00:07:22,343 --> 00:07:26,411
to remain here in the
care and comfort of our eye.

96
00:07:26,413 --> 00:07:30,449
Let not thy mother lose
her prayers, Hamlet.

97
00:07:30,451 --> 00:07:32,117
Stay with us,

98
00:07:32,119 --> 00:07:34,953
go not to Wittenberg.

99
00:07:34,955 --> 00:07:37,489
I shall in all my best obey you, madam.

100
00:08:02,015 --> 00:08:04,983
<i>That this too, too solid
flesh would melt,</i>

101
00:08:04,985 --> 00:08:08,987
<i>thaw, and resolve itself into a dew.</i>

102
00:08:08,989 --> 00:08:13,692
<i>Or that the Everlasting had not fixed
his canon 'gainst self-slaughter.</i>

103
00:08:13,694 --> 00:08:15,694
<i>God.</i>

104
00:08:15,696 --> 00:08:18,530
<i>God. How weary, stale, flat,
and unprofitable</i>

105
00:08:18,532 --> 00:08:20,632
<i>seem to me all the uses of this world.</i>

106
00:08:22,669 --> 00:08:25,771
<i>'Tis an unweeded garden
that grows to seed.</i>

107
00:08:25,773 --> 00:08:28,874
<i>Things rank and gross
in nature possess it merely.</i>

108
00:08:30,744 --> 00:08:32,911
<i>That it should come to this!</i>

109
00:08:32,913 --> 00:08:35,547
<i>But two months dead,
nay, not so much, not two.</i>

110
00:08:35,549 --> 00:08:38,183
<i>So excellent a king that was, to this,</i>

111
00:08:38,185 --> 00:08:41,753
<i>Hyperion to a satyr.</i>

112
00:08:43,924 --> 00:08:46,491
<i>So loving to my mother that he might
not beteem the winds of heaven</i>

113
00:08:46,493 --> 00:08:49,861
<i>visit her face too roughly.</i>

114
00:08:49,863 --> 00:08:52,597
<i>Why, she would hang on him,
as if increase of appetite</i>

115
00:08:52,599 --> 00:08:54,466
<i>had grown by what it fed on.</i>

116
00:08:54,468 --> 00:08:57,102
<i>And yet, within a month...</i>

117
00:08:57,104 --> 00:09:00,005
<i>I may not think on it.</i>

118
00:09:00,007 --> 00:09:01,973
<i>Frailty, thy name is woman.</i>

119
00:09:03,644 --> 00:09:06,077
<i>A little month</i>

120
00:09:06,079 --> 00:09:10,449
<i>or ere these shoes were old with which
she followed my poor father's body</i>

121
00:09:10,451 --> 00:09:13,885
<i>like Niobe, all tears...
Why she, even she...</i>

122
00:09:13,887 --> 00:09:16,121
<i>God!</i>

123
00:09:16,123 --> 00:09:19,925
<i>A beast that wants discourse of
reason would have mourned longer.</i>

124
00:09:19,927 --> 00:09:22,027
<i>Married with my uncle,
my father's brothe, r</i>

125
00:09:22,029 --> 00:09:25,130
<i>but no more like my father
than I to Hercules.</i>

126
00:09:25,132 --> 00:09:27,098
<i>Within a month.</i>

127
00:09:27,100 --> 00:09:29,835
<i>Ere yet the salt of
most unrighteous tears</i>

128
00:09:29,837 --> 00:09:33,738
<i>had left the flushing in her
galled eyes... she married.</i>

129
00:09:33,740 --> 00:09:36,475
<i>Most wicked speed,</i>

130
00:09:36,477 --> 00:09:40,245
<i>to post with such
dexterity to incestuous sheets!</i>

131
00:09:41,782 --> 00:09:44,850
<i>It is not nor it cannot come to good.</i>

132
00:09:44,852 --> 00:09:48,720
<i>But break, my heart,
for I must hold my tongue.</i>

133
00:10:26,627 --> 00:10:30,128
What make you from Wittenberg, Marcellus?

134
00:10:30,130 --> 00:10:32,030
- My good lord.
- I'm very glad to see you.

135
00:10:32,032 --> 00:10:33,765
Good even, sir.

136
00:10:35,302 --> 00:10:37,269
But what, in faith,
make you from Wittenberg?

137
00:10:37,271 --> 00:10:41,172
A truant disposition, good my lord.

138
00:10:41,174 --> 00:10:43,875
What is your affair in Elsinore?

139
00:10:43,877 --> 00:10:45,777
My lord, I came to see
your father's funeral.

140
00:10:45,779 --> 00:10:47,746
I pray thee, do not
mock me, fellow student,

141
00:10:47,748 --> 00:10:49,648
I think it was to see
my mother's wedding.

142
00:10:49,650 --> 00:10:52,083
Indeed, my lord, it followed hard upon.

143
00:10:52,085 --> 00:10:54,019
Thrift, thrift, Horatio.

144
00:10:54,021 --> 00:10:58,323
The funeral baked meats did coldly
furnish forth the marriage tables.

145
00:10:58,325 --> 00:11:01,159
Would I had met my dearest foe in heaven

146
00:11:01,161 --> 00:11:03,795
or ever I had seen that day, Horatio.

147
00:11:05,065 --> 00:11:06,932
<i>My father...</i>

148
00:11:06,934 --> 00:11:09,200
<i>methinks I see my father.</i>

149
00:11:09,202 --> 00:11:11,803
Where, my lord?

150
00:11:11,805 --> 00:11:14,172
In my mind's eye.

151
00:11:15,842 --> 00:11:19,010
I saw him once, he was a goodly king.

152
00:11:19,012 --> 00:11:22,914
He was a man, take him for all in all,
I shall not look upon his like again.

153
00:11:23,984 --> 00:11:27,152
<i>I think I saw him...</i>

154
00:11:27,154 --> 00:11:29,054
<i>yester-night.</i>

155
00:11:29,056 --> 00:11:31,656
Saw? Who?

156
00:11:31,658 --> 00:11:34,326
My lord, the king. Your father.

157
00:11:34,328 --> 00:11:36,695
The king my father.

158
00:11:37,998 --> 00:11:40,632
Season your admiration for a while

159
00:11:40,634 --> 00:11:42,300
<i>with an attent ear, till I may deliver</i>

160
00:11:42,302 --> 00:11:44,135
upon the witness of these gentlemen

161
00:11:44,137 --> 00:11:46,237
this marvel to you.

162
00:11:46,239 --> 00:11:48,340
In the dead waste in middle of the night,

163
00:11:48,342 --> 00:11:50,108
the apparition comes.

164
00:11:59,853 --> 00:12:01,886
<i>Where was this?</i>

165
00:12:01,888 --> 00:12:04,155
<i>My lord, upon the platform
where we watched.</i>

166
00:12:04,157 --> 00:12:06,024
'Tis here.

167
00:12:16,670 --> 00:12:18,169
Did you not speak to it?

168
00:12:18,171 --> 00:12:19,404
<i>My lord, I did.</i>

169
00:12:19,406 --> 00:12:21,773
But answer made it none.

170
00:12:21,775 --> 00:12:25,243
Yet once methought it lifted up its
head and did address itself to motion

171
00:12:25,245 --> 00:12:27,278
like as it would speak.

172
00:12:29,149 --> 00:12:31,883
<i>Stay, illusion.</i>

173
00:12:31,885 --> 00:12:35,387
If thou hast any sound or use of voice,

174
00:12:35,389 --> 00:12:37,122
speak to me.

175
00:12:38,392 --> 00:12:41,326
It is offended.

176
00:12:41,328 --> 00:12:43,128
If there be any good thing to be done,

177
00:12:43,130 --> 00:12:47,098
that may to thee do ease and grace to me,

178
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:49,000
speak to me.

179
00:12:50,203 --> 00:12:53,304
Speak, speak!

180
00:12:53,306 --> 00:12:55,974
<i>I charge thee, speak.</i>

181
00:13:02,416 --> 00:13:04,749
'Tis very strange.

182
00:13:04,751 --> 00:13:06,951
As I do live, my lord, 'tis true.

183
00:13:06,953 --> 00:13:08,720
And we did think it writ down in our duty

184
00:13:08,722 --> 00:13:10,088
to let you know of it.

185
00:13:10,090 --> 00:13:11,823
<i>Indeed, indeed.</i>

186
00:13:11,825 --> 00:13:15,727
But this troubles me.

187
00:13:15,729 --> 00:13:18,897
- Hold you the watch again tonight?
- I do, my lord.

188
00:13:21,735 --> 00:13:23,902
What looked he...

189
00:13:23,904 --> 00:13:25,236
frowningly?

190
00:13:25,238 --> 00:13:27,872
A countenance more
in sorrow than in anger.

191
00:13:27,874 --> 00:13:30,709
- And fixed his eyes upon you?
<i>- Most constantly.</i>

192
00:13:30,711 --> 00:13:32,210
I would I had been there.

193
00:13:32,212 --> 00:13:33,845
It would have much amazed you.

194
00:13:33,847 --> 00:13:36,381
I will watch tonight.

195
00:13:36,383 --> 00:13:40,318
I'll speak to it, though Hell itself
should gape and bid me hold my peace.

196
00:13:40,320 --> 00:13:43,855
And I pray you all, if you have
hitherto concealed this sight,

197
00:13:43,857 --> 00:13:45,824
let it be tenable in your silence still.

198
00:13:45,826 --> 00:13:47,859
And whatsoever else shall
hap tonight, give it an...

199
00:13:47,861 --> 00:13:50,862
understanding, but no tongue.

200
00:13:50,864 --> 00:13:52,097
I will require your loves.

201
00:13:52,099 --> 00:13:54,099
So, fare you well.

202
00:13:59,473 --> 00:14:02,474
Upon the platform, 'twixt
11 and 12, I'll visit you.

203
00:14:02,476 --> 00:14:04,476
Our duty to your honor.

204
00:14:04,478 --> 00:14:07,746
Your loves, as mine to you. Farewell.

205
00:14:12,219 --> 00:14:15,086
<i>Would the night were come.</i>

206
00:14:15,088 --> 00:14:19,157
<i>Till then sit still, my soul.</i>

207
00:14:19,159 --> 00:14:22,327
<i>Foul deeds will rise,</i>

208
00:14:22,329 --> 00:14:26,164
<i>though all the earth
o'erwhelm them to men's eyes.</i>

209
00:14:29,169 --> 00:14:32,971
<i>Perhaps he loves you now, and now no</i>

210
00:14:32,973 --> 00:14:36,307
soil nor cautel doth besmirch
the virtue of his will.

211
00:14:37,511 --> 00:14:40,411
But you must fear,

212
00:14:42,182 --> 00:14:46,050
his virtue weighed,
his will is not his own.

213
00:14:46,052 --> 00:14:49,487
For he himself is subject to his birth.

214
00:14:57,063 --> 00:14:59,330
He may not, as unvalued persons do,

215
00:14:59,332 --> 00:15:02,167
carve for himself,

216
00:15:02,169 --> 00:15:06,504
for on his choice depends the health
and safety of this whole state

217
00:15:06,506 --> 00:15:08,406
and therefore must his
choice be circumscribed

218
00:15:08,408 --> 00:15:10,074
unto the voice and yielding of that body

219
00:15:10,076 --> 00:15:12,443
whereof he is the head.

220
00:15:12,445 --> 00:15:15,380
<i>Then if he says he loves you, it fits
your wisdom so far to believe it</i>

221
00:15:15,382 --> 00:15:19,284
<i>as he in his particular act and
place may give his saying deed,</i>

222
00:15:19,286 --> 00:15:22,487
<i>which is no further than the main
voice of Denmark goes withal.</i>

223
00:15:28,929 --> 00:15:32,497
Then weigh what loss your honor
may sustain if with too...

224
00:15:32,499 --> 00:15:36,367
credent ear you list his songs, or...

225
00:15:36,369 --> 00:15:38,436
lose your heart,

226
00:15:43,844 --> 00:15:46,411
or your chaste treasure

227
00:15:46,413 --> 00:15:51,082
open to his unmastered importunity.

228
00:15:56,323 --> 00:15:58,489
Fear it, Ophelia.

229
00:16:00,460 --> 00:16:03,628
Fear it, my dear sister.

230
00:16:03,630 --> 00:16:05,396
And keep you in the
rear of your affection

231
00:16:05,398 --> 00:16:08,299
out of the shot and danger of desire.

232
00:16:11,905 --> 00:16:14,639
Best safety lies in fear.

233
00:16:18,411 --> 00:16:21,646
Youth to itself rebels,

234
00:16:21,648 --> 00:16:24,148
though none else near.

235
00:16:26,519 --> 00:16:30,054
I shall the effect
of this good lesson keep

236
00:16:30,056 --> 00:16:32,357
as watchman to my heart.

237
00:16:34,294 --> 00:16:38,129
But, good my brother, do not,
as some ungracious pastors do,

238
00:16:38,131 --> 00:16:40,665
show me the steep
and thorny way to heaven

239
00:16:40,667 --> 00:16:43,034
while like a puffed
and reckless libertine himself

240
00:16:43,036 --> 00:16:47,005
the primrose path of dalliance treads

241
00:16:47,007 --> 00:16:48,973
and wrecks not his own creed.

242
